data.content:
Yes — the direct cast will throw an `InvalidCastException` on failure instead of giving a clear test message. Use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType` (or its generic overload):

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    var handler = (EmailHandler)result;
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

Or combine the type check and cast with **pattern matching**:

```csharp
Assert.IsTrue(result is EmailHandler handler);
Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
```

`Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>` is the most idiomatic MSTest approach — it produces a clear failure message like *"Expected type: EmailHandler. Actual type: SmsHandler."*
